declarations.comments:
This type class asserts that types `a` and `b`
are equal.

The functional dependencies and the single
instance below will force the two type arguments
to unify when either one is known.

Note: any instance will necessarily overlap with
`refl` below, so instances of this class should
not be defined in libraries.
declarations.title: TypeEquals

declarations.comments: Value proxy for kind `Type` types.
declarations.title: Proxy

declarations.comments:
A proxy data type whose type parameter is a type of kind `# Type` (a row
of types).

Commonly used for specialising a function with a quantified type.
For example, suppose we have an identity function for records of type:
```purescript
recordIdentity :: forall row . RProxy row -> Record row -> Record row
recordIdentity _ rec = rec
```
Then applying this function to an `RProxy` with a specialised type
allows us to specify a concrete type for `row`:
```purescript
:t recordIdentity (RProxy :: RProxy ( x :: Int, y :: Int ))
{ x :: Int, y :: Int } -> { x :: Int, y :: Int }
```
Here `row` has been specialised to `( x :: Int, y :: Int )`.
declarations.title: RProxy

declarations.comments: The Lacks type class asserts that a label does not occur in a given row.
declarations.title: Lacks

declarations.comments:
The Union type class is used to compute the union of two rows of types
(left-biased, including duplicates).

The third type argument represents the union of the first two.
declarations.title: Union

declarations.comments:
A proxy data type whose type parameter is a type of kind `RowList`.

Commonly used for specialising a function with a quantified type.
declarations.title: RLProxy

declarations.comments:
Convert a RowList to a row of types.
The inverse of this operation is `RowToList`.
declarations.title: ListToRow

declarations.comments:
Compiler solved type class for generating a `RowList` from a closed row
of types.  Entries are sorted by label and duplicates are preserved in
the order they appeared in the row.
declarations.title: RowToList

declarations.comments:
The Cons type class is a 4-way relation which asserts that one row of
types can be obtained from another by inserting a new label/type pair on
the left.
declarations.title: Cons

declarations.comments: The Lacks type class asserts that a label does not occur in a given row.
declarations.title: Lacks

declarations.comments: The Nub type class is used to remove duplicate labels from rows.
declarations.title: Nub

declarations.comments:
The Union type class is used to compute the union of two rows of types
(left-biased, including duplicates).

The third type argument represents the union of the first two.
declarations.title: Union

declarations.comments: Type application for rows.
declarations.title: RowApply

declarations.comments:
Applies a type alias of open rows to a set of rows. The primary use case
this operator is as convenient sugar for combining open rows without
parentheses.
```purescript
type Rows1 r = (a :: Int, b :: String | r)
type Rows2 r = (c :: Boolean | r)
type Rows3 r = (Rows1 + Rows2 + r)
type Rows4 r = (d :: String | Rows1 + Rows2 + r)
```
declarations.title: type (+)
